{"title_page": "Neshaminy School District", "text_new": "{{Infobox school district\n | name                   = Neshaminy School District\n | motto                  = \n | logo                   = NESHAMINY-COLOR.png\n | image                  = Map of Bucks County Pennsylvania School Districts.png\n | image_size             = \n | type                   = Public\n | streetaddress          = 2250 Langhorne-Yardley Road\n | city                   = [[Langhorne, Pennsylvania|Langhorne]]\n | state                  = [[Pennsylvania]]\n | province               = \n | county                 = \n | postcode               = \n | postalcode             = \n | zipcode                = \n | country                = USA\n | budget                 = \n | established            = \n | grades                 = K-12\n | other                  = \n | region                 = \n | superintendent         = Joseph Jones III\n | teachers               = 641\n | ratio                  = \n | enrollment             = 9,037 <ref>Neshaminy School District BoardDocs, January 2, 2020</ref>\n | tuition                = \n | athletics_conference   = \n | colors                 = \n | free_label             = \n | free_text              = \n | free_label2            = \n | free_text2             = \n | free_label3            = \n | free_text3             = \n | mapimage1              = \n | mapimage1size          = \n | mapimage2              = \n | mapimage2size          = \n | schedule               = \n | information            = \n | website                = {{url|neshaminy.org}}\n}}\n'''Neshaminy School District''' serves the eastern Pennsylvania municipalities of [[Middletown Township, Bucks County, Pennsylvania|Middletown Township]], [[Langhorne, Pennsylvania|Langhorne]], [[Langhorne Manor, Pennsylvania|Langhorne Manor]], [[Penndel]], [[Hulmeville]], and [[Lower Southampton Township, Pennsylvania|Lower Southampton Township]] in [[Bucks County]], [[Pennsylvania]]. Students from the Middletown divisions of [[Levittown, Pennsylvania|Levittown]] also attend these schools. Neshaminy School District  encompasses approximately {{convert|28|sqmi|km2}}. According to 2000 federal census data, it serves a resident population of 69,638. Per Neshaminy School District documents, as of January, 2020 the Neshaminy School District provided basic educational services to 9,037 pupils.<ref>Neshamniny BoardDocs Enrollment Totals, January, 2020</ref> Full-day kindergarten in all elementary schools was added starting in the 2014\u20132015 school year.<ref>http://www.buckslocalnews.com/the_advance/neshaminy-to-launch-full-day-kindergarten-in-elementary-schools-scraps/article_3eb5ccb9-27dc-5582-982e-80a5bc0ef559.html</ref> A 1:1 Technology program was implemented beginning in 2015, deploying [[IPad|iPads]] for students in grades K-1 and [[Chromebook|Chromebooks]] for students in grades 2-12.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://http/%3A%2F%2Fwww.neshaminy.org%2Fsite%2Fdefault.aspx%3FPageID%3D30916|title=Technology Services / 1:1 Deployment * Learning Anytime - Anywhere|website=http|language=en|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref>\n\nThe Neshaminy School District serves a large and diverse population. Students comprise many different racial, ethnic, and economic backgrounds. District residents represent a wide range from lower-middle-class to highly affluent. Neshaminy is a Blue-Ribbon awarding school district, with Maple Point Middle School having received the award, as well as Neshaminy High School. In February, 2017 the Neshaminy School District received the Charlotte F. Lockhart Award for Excellence in Literacy Education.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://midweekwire.com/2017/03/06/neshaminy-school-district-teachers-receive-honors/ |title=Neshaminy School District teachers receive honors |author=Timothy Reilly |date=March 6, 2017 |access-date=March 16, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170317055056/https://midweekwire.com/2017/03/06/neshaminy-school-district-teachers-receive-honors/ |archive-date=March 17, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and was named a 'Best Community for Music Education by the National Association of Music Marketers in 2017, 2018 and 2019.<ref>https://www.neshaminy.org/site/default.aspx?PageType=3&DomainID=1&ModuleInstanceID=40557&ViewID=6446EE88-D30C-497E-9316-3F8874B3E108&RenderLoc=0&FlexDataID=64279&PageID=1</ref> Neshaminy HS was named a 'Best High School' by U.S. News & World Report in 2017, earning a silver medal.<ref>https://www.usnews.com/education/best-high-schools/pennsylvania/districts/neshaminy-sd/neshaminy-high-school-17121</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nThe first public school in the area was established in [[Langhorne, Pennsylvania|Langhorne]] in 1836, and the District as it is known today was formed in 1950 by a conglomeration of smaller municipal districts.<ref>https://www.neshaminy.org/domain/2368</ref>\n\nMany Neshaminy facilities were constructed during the 1950s and 1960s following the development of the [[Levittown]] community at the southeast portion of the district. In 1975 a second high school was added (Maple Point) but was closed in 1982<ref>http://neshaminyfootball.com/history/notable_eras/maple_point/1975-1982.htm</ref> and later converted into a middle school following a renovation project completed in 1993. Eisenhower Elementary School and Neshaminy Middle School were closed and the properties sold.<ref>http://www.buckslocalnews.com/the_advance/former-neshaminy-middle-school-sold-to-st-mary-medical-center/article_96ba38ec-fdcc-5a1c-ab49-54aeb6aa2a9d.html</ref><ref>http://levittownnow.com/2013/09/03/settlement-on-former-school-pending/</ref>\n\nIn June 2006, the Neshaminy School District began a massive $82 million renovation of Neshaminy High School, which was originally constructed as a combination high school and junior high school in the 1950s. Much of the original structure was demolished and completely rebuilt. The auditorium, 2 gymnasiums and circular library media center were all pre-existing but received extensive renovations. New classrooms, science labs, music rooms, tech education rooms, offices and common areas were added along with new parking lots and an expanded bus loading area.\n\nIn 2015 the district started a three-phase 'Road Map' project to update older buildings, close three elementary schools to account for excess capacity (Heckman ES, Lower Southampton ES and Everett ES), and construct a new elementary school on the site of the old Tawanka Elementary School, which was demolished. Significant upgrades to several existing buildings (Sandburg MS, Poquessing MS, Ferderbar ES, Hoover ES, Miller ES and Schweitzer ES) were completed with funding from the federal Guaranteed Energy Savings Act including air conditioning, energy-efficient windows, roofing, lighting and other electrical upgrades. Additional upgrades included security features and online visitor registration kiosks.<ref>https://www.neshaminy.org/cms/lib/PA01000466/Centricity/Domain/1777/flier-042115-sm.pdf</ref> The final phase of the Road Map project was completed in August, 2017.<ref>https://www.neshaminy.org/Page/37840</ref>\n\n==School board==\nNeshaminy School District is represented by a 9-member School Board of Directors. The district is split into three regions (Region 1, Region 2, and Region 3). each of which elect three representatives. The 2019\u20132020 School Board President is Stephen Pirritano (Region 1) and the Vice-President is John Allen (Region 2). The Seven Other Board Members are Marty Sullivan (Region 3),Cyndie Bowman (Region 1), Irene M.Boyle (Region 3),Tina Hollenbach (Region 1), Adam J. Kovitz (Region 2), David Marrington (Region 3), And Paul C. Saraullo (Region 2) Paul Is the newest Member of the School Board beating Incumbent Bob Feather (Region 2). For a Region 2 seat on  November 5, 2019 (Election Day) and then was sworn onto the School Board on December 2, 2019 <ref>https://www.neshaminy.org/domain/1967</ref> The Board normally meets at the District Administration office in Maple Point Middle School twice a month. All meetings are broadcast on the NSDTV channel on Verizon and Comcast cable TV systems in the Lower Bucks County area or can viewed on the [https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCWSzcKzLZt0N9_artuBEYpA/videos Neshaminy School Board Channel on \nYouTube]\n\n\n\n==Intermediate Unit==\nNeshaminy School District is served by [https://www.bucksiu.org/ Bucks County Intermediate Unit #22.]\n\n[[File:NHS-1.jpg|thumb|Aerial view of Neshaminy High School]]\n\n==High school==\n===[[Neshaminy High School]]===\n\nNeshaminy High School is located at 2001 Old Lincoln Highway in Langhorne, PA. Enrollment as of January, 2020 is 2,573 students in grades 9-12. 327 Neshaminy students attend the Bucks County Technical High School. Neshaminy has a graduation rate of 95% and offers a rich variety of courses and co-curricular activities including 20 Advanced Placement courses<ref>https://www.usnews.com/education/best-high-schools/pennsylvania/districts/neshaminy-sd/neshaminy-high-school-17121/test-scores</ref>\n*[https://futurereadypa.org/Performance/123238108010045189089083010012180228205159115037/001232060191235024099229004013137247093037069080 Future Ready PA Index - Neshaminy High School] c\n\n==Middle schools==\n\n===Maple Point Middle School===\nLocated at 2250 Langhorne-Yardley Road, Langhorne. Enrollment as of January, 2020 is 1345 students in grades 5-8.\n*[https://futurereadypa.org/Performance/028228244236222235072090060245016072198063058188/151193013047060120155203102247122228153161155088 Future Ready PA Index - Maple Point Middle School]\n\n===Poquessing Middle School===\nLocated at 300 Heights Lane, Feasterville Trevose. Enrollment as January, 2020 is 931 students in grades 5-8.\n*[https://futurereadypa.org/Performance/089118177148132010036037029046024109092058107246/163037174175021028191115250006186134249130212215 Future Ready PA Index - Poquessing Middle School]\n\n===Carl Sandburg Middle School===\nLocated at 30 Harmony Road, Levittown. Enrollment as of January, 2020 is 755 students in grades 5-8.\n*[https://futurereadypa.org/Performance/251094080059105233137066092208074134166054234040/038139125129234005186169160252087050222143243012 Future Ready PA Index - Carl Sandburg Middle School]\n\n==Elementary schools==\n===Pearl S. Buck Elementary School===\nLocated at 143 Top Road, Levittown. Enrollment as of January, 2020 is 587 students in grades K-4. \n*[https://futurereadypa.org/Performance/223157169143250115000180180069023045096103149197/140147168146115058140197069003123203154180142014 Future Ready PA Index - Pearl S. Buck Elementary School]\n\n===Joseph E Ferderbar Elementary School===\nLocated at 300 Heights Lane, Feasterville. Enrollment as of January, 2020 is 473 students in grades K-4.\n*[https://futurereadypa.org/Performance/250057129020160133134009124218237132080121090200/023181213017026130127006125104035143143036117061239059038048191084007184056093014176071032031043 Future Ready PA Index - Joseph Ferderbar Elementary School]\n\n===Herbert Hoover Elementary School===\nLocated at 500 Trenton Road, Langhorne. Enrollment as of January, 2020 is 672 students in grades K-4.\n*[https://futurereadypa.org/Performance/132029143071137021091168188065001224163062100227/231234145094018140201190065209170156151237055191 Future Ready PA Index - Herbert Hoover Elementary School]\n\n===Walter Miller Elementary School=== \nLocated at 10 Cobalt Ridge Drive in Levittown, PA. Enrollment as of January, 2020 is 506 students in grades K-4.\n*[https://futurereadypa.org/Performance/018112152024132181089103157233184119157143252188/116088217111201144099251091195017161209231192068 Future Ready PA Index - Walter Miller Elementary School]\n\n===Albert Schweitzer Elementary School===\nLocated at 30 Harmony Lane in Levittown, PA. Enrollment as of January, 2020 is 432 students in grades K-4.\n*[https://futurereadypa.org/Performance/061056037221133008241050044000007061167050211005/020052196202219029081226234081073199222106051122091108205182052189089177162052212065030069216008 Future Ready PA Index - Albert Schweitzer Elementary School]\n\n===Tawanka Elementary School=== \nLocated at 2055 Brownsville Road in Feasterville, PA. The current building was completed in August, 2016 and opened for the 2016\u20132017 school year. It was built in the same site as the previous Tawanka Elementary School building, which opened in 1964 and was demolished to make way for the new facility. Enrollment as of January, 2020 is 763 students in grades K-4.\n*[https://futurereadypa.org/Performance/126108161194059186133218245145047247219093020229/025209004210100222090107233227095155008174133169 Future Ready PA Index - Tawanka Elementary School].\n\n==Special education==\n\nNeshaminy School District provides the following services:<ref>https://www.neshaminy.org/domain/2643</ref>\n\n'''Learning support''' \u2013 for children whose greatest need of support is in the areas of reading, writing, math, or speaking or listening related to academics.\n\n'''Emotional support''' \u2013 for children whose greatest need is for social, emotional, and behavioral help\nLife skills support \u2013 for children whose greatest need is to learn academic, functional, or vocational skills that will allow them to live and work independently.\n\n'''Blind and visually impaired support''' \u2013 for children who require services related to visual impairments or blindness. The IEP for these students must address the extent to which Braille will be taught and used.\n\n'''Deaf and hard of hearing support''' \u2013 for children who require services related to deafness or hearing impairment. The IEP for these students must include a communication plan to address language and communication needs\nSpeech and language support \u2013 for children who have speech and language impairments and require services to develop communication skills.\n\n'''Physical support''' \u2013 for children who have a physical disability and require services in functional motor skill development.\n\n'''Autistic support''' \u2013 for children with autism who require services in the areas of communication, social skills, or behavior.\n\n'''Multiple disabilities support''' \u2013 for children with more than one disability, the combination of which results in severe impairment, and who require services in academic, functional, or vocational skills necessary for independent living.\n\n==Gifted education==\n\nNeshaminy School District recognizes the unique abilities of intellectually gifted students and strives to meet their individual needs. Based on multiple criteria, students with outstanding intellectual ability and creativity and the need for a specialized educational experience are identified to participate in the AE (Academic Enrichment) program. AE classes provide opportunities to promote the growth of skills and knowledge necessary for gifted students to achieve their potential and to fulfill their future roles in our ever-changing global society.<ref>https://www.neshaminy.org/domain/1916</ref>\n\nIn 2015 a comprehensive review of the Academic enrichment was started and a Task Force report presented in June, 2016.<ref>https://www.neshaminy.org/cms/lib/PA01000466/Centricity/Domain/1916/AE-report-040116.pdf</ref> Based on the recommendations from this report changes were made to the program.<ref>https://www.neshaminy.org/cms/lib/PA01000466/Centricity/Domain/1916/ae-recommendations-121515a.pdf</ref>\n\n== Education Foundation ==\nThe non-profit 501(c)(3) [https://www.neshaminy.org/nef Neshaminy Education Foundation] was established as part of the District's Strategic Plan in 1993. It supports classroom grants and several scholarships for graduating seniors through a variety of fundraising activities throughout the year. The Foundation is managed by a group of volunteer Board Members who meet monthly during the school year.\n\n==Budget==\n\nIn June, 2019 the Neshaminy Board of School Directors adopted a Final Operating Budget of all funds in the amount of $185,853,953 for the 2019-2020 school year.\n\nOf this amount $119,939,505 was for instruction,$50,807,313 for support services and $1,963,207 for non-instructional services. \n\nAn tax increase of 2.3% (the PA Act 1 index maximum) was approved. This is the third such tax increase since 2010.<ref>https://www.neshaminy.org/site/handlers/filedownload.ashx?moduleinstanceid=43524&dataid=74979&FileName=2019-20%20Final%20PDE%202028%20for%20website.pdf</ref>\n\n==Contracts==\n'''Neshaminy Federation of Teachers''': The current teacher contract runs from July, 2019 to June, 2024.<ref>https://www.neshaminy.org/Page/37053</ref>\n\n'''Neshaminy Educational Support Professional Association''': The current support contract runs from July, 2018 - June, 2022.<ref>http://go.boarddocs.com/pa/nesh/Board.nsf/goto?open&id=BJ6QGH693F28</ref>\n\n==Real estate taxes==\nIn June, 2019 the School Board approved the third tax hike since the 2009\u20132010 school year, a 2.3% increase. This is the maximum increase allowed under the Pennsylvania Act 1 index. The district was granted an exemption that would have allowed a higher increase but the board chose not to use that option.<ref>http://levittownnow.com/2018/06/11/tax-increase-proposed-in-2018-2019-neshaminy-school-district-budget/</ref>\nThe district offers a Senior Citizen Tax Assistance Program each year. Eligible low-income seniors can apply for a rebate of up to $650.<ref>https://www.neshaminy.org/Page/758</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.neshaminy.org Neshaminy's official website]\n*[http://neshaminy.pa.aft.org/ Neshaminy Federation of Teachers]\n*[https://neshaminyesp.psealocals.org/ Neshaminy Educational Support Professional Association]\n*[https://www3.bucksiu.org/ Bucks County Intermediate Unit]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCWSzcKzLZt0N9_artuBEYpA/videos Board Meeting YouTube Channel]\n\n{{Bucks County, Pennsylvania School Districts}}\n\n[[Category:School districts in Bucks County, Pennsylvania]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox school district\n | name                   = Neshaminy School District\n | motto                  = \n | logo                   = NESHAMINY-COLOR.png\n | image                  = Map of Bucks County Pennsylvania School Districts.png\n | image_size             = \n | type                   = Public\n | streetaddress          = 2250 Langhorne-Yardley Road\n | city                   = [[Langhorne, Pennsylvania|Langhorne]]\n | state                  = [[Pennsylvania]]\n | province               = \n | county                 = \n | postcode               = \n | postalcode             = \n | zipcode                = \n | country                = USA\n | budget                 = \n | established            = \n | grades                 = K-12\n | other                  = \n | region                 = \n | superintendent         = Joseph Jones III\n | teachers               = 641\n | ratio                  = \n | enrollment             = 9,037 <ref>Neshaminy School District BoardDocs, January 2, 2020</ref>\n | tuition                = \n | athletics_conference   = \n | colors                 = \n | free_label             = \n | free_text              = \n | free_label2            = \n | free_text2             = \n | free_label3            = \n | free_text3             = \n | mapimage1              = \n | mapimage1size          = \n | mapimage2              = \n | mapimage2size          = \n | schedule               = \n | information            = \n | website                = {{url|neshaminy.org}}\n}}\n'''Neshaminy School District''' serves the eastern Pennsylvania municipalities of [[Middletown Township, Bucks County, Pennsylvania|Middletown Township]], [[Langhorne, Pennsylvania|Langhorne]], [[Langhorne Manor, Pennsylvania|Langhorne Manor]], [[Penndel]], [[Hulmeville]], and [[Lower Southampton Township, Pennsylvania|Lower Southampton Township]] in [[Bucks County]], [[Pennsylvania]]. Students from the Middletown divisions of [[Levittown, Pennsylvania|Levittown]] also attend these schools. Neshaminy School District  encompasses approximately {{convert|28|sqmi|km2}}. According to 2000 federal census data, it serves a resident population of 69,638. Per Neshaminy School District documents, as of January, 2020 the Neshaminy School District provided basic educational services to 9,037 pupils.<ref>Neshamniny BoardDocs Enrollment Totals, January, 2020</ref> Full-day kindergarten in all elementary schools was added starting in the 2014\u20132015 school year.<ref>http://www.buckslocalnews.com/the_advance/neshaminy-to-launch-full-day-kindergarten-in-elementary-schools-scraps/article_3eb5ccb9-27dc-5582-982e-80a5bc0ef559.html</ref> A 1:1 Technology program was implemented beginning in 2015, deploying [[IPad|iPads]] for students in grades K-1 and [[Chromebook|Chromebooks]] for students in grades 2-12.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://http/%3A%2F%2Fwww.neshaminy.org%2Fsite%2Fdefault.aspx%3FPageID%3D30916|title=Technology Services / 1:1 Deployment * Learning Anytime - Anywhere|website=http|language=en|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref>\n\nThe Neshaminy School District serves a large and diverse population. Students comprise many different racial, ethnic, and economic backgrounds. District residents represent a wide range from lower-middle-class to highly affluent. Neshaminy is a Blue-Ribbon awarding school district, with Maple Point Middle School having received the award, as well as Neshaminy High School. In February, 2017 the Neshaminy School District received the Charlotte F. Lockhart Award for Excellence in Literacy Education.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://midweekwire.com/2017/03/06/neshaminy-school-district-teachers-receive-honors/ |title=Neshaminy School District teachers receive honors |author=Timothy Reilly |date=March 6, 2017 |access-date=March 16, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170317055056/https://midweekwire.com/2017/03/06/neshaminy-school-district-teachers-receive-honors/ |archive-date=March 17, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and was named a 'Best Community for Music Education by the National Association of Music Marketers in 2017, 2018 and 2019.<ref>https://www.neshaminy.org/site/default.aspx?PageType=3&DomainID=1&ModuleInstanceID=40557&ViewID=6446EE88-D30C-497E-9316-3F8874B3E108&RenderLoc=0&FlexDataID=64279&PageID=1</ref> Neshaminy HS was named a 'Best High School' by U.S. News & World Report in 2017, earning a silver medal.<ref>https://www.usnews.com/education/best-high-schools/pennsylvania/districts/neshaminy-sd/neshaminy-high-school-17121</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nThe first public school in the area was established in [[Langhorne, Pennsylvania|Langhorne]] in 1836, and the District as it is known today was formed in 1950 by a conglomeration of smaller municipal districts.<ref>https://www.neshaminy.org/domain/2368</ref>\n\nMany Neshaminy facilities were constructed during the 1950s and 1960s following the development of the [[Levittown]] community at the southeast portion of the district. In 1975 a second high school was added (Maple Point) but was closed in 1982<ref>http://neshaminyfootball.com/history/notable_eras/maple_point/1975-1982.htm</ref> and later converted into a middle school following a renovation project completed in 1993. Eisenhower Elementary School and Neshaminy Middle School were closed and the properties sold.<ref>http://www.buckslocalnews.com/the_advance/former-neshaminy-middle-school-sold-to-st-mary-medical-center/article_96ba38ec-fdcc-5a1c-ab49-54aeb6aa2a9d.html</ref><ref>http://levittownnow.com/2013/09/03/settlement-on-former-school-pending/</ref>\n\nIn June 2006, the Neshaminy School District began a massive $82 million renovation of Neshaminy High School, which was originally constructed as a combination high school and junior high school in the 1950s. Much of the original structure was demolished and completely rebuilt. The auditorium, 2 gymnasiums and circular library media center were all pre-existing but received extensive renovations. New classrooms, science labs, music rooms, tech education rooms, offices and common areas were added along with new parking lots and an expanded bus loading area.\n\nIn 2015 the district started a three-phase 'Road Map' project to update older buildings, close three elementary schools to account for excess capacity (Heckman ES, Lower Southampton ES and Everett ES), and construct a new elementary school on the site of the old Tawanka Elementary School, which was demolished. Significant upgrades to several existing buildings (Sandburg MS, Poquessing MS, Ferderbar ES, Hoover ES, Miller ES and Schweitzer ES) were completed with funding from the federal Guaranteed Energy Savings Act including air conditioning, energy-efficient windows, roofing, lighting and other electrical upgrades. Additional upgrades included security features and online visitor registration kiosks.<ref>https://www.neshaminy.org/cms/lib/PA01000466/Centricity/Domain/1777/flier-042115-sm.pdf</ref> The final phase of the Road Map project was completed in August, 2017.<ref>https://www.neshaminy.org/Page/37840</ref>\n\n==School board==\nNeshaminy School District is represented by a 9-member School Board of Directors. The district is split into three regions (Region 1, Region 2, and Region 3). each of which elect three representatives. The 2019\u20132020 School Board President is Stephen Pirritano (Region 1) and the Vice-President is John Allen (Region 2). The Seven Other Board Members are Marty Sullivan (Region 3),Cyndie Bowman (Region 1), Irene M.Boyle (Region 3),Tina Hollenbach (Region 1), Adam J. Kovitz (Region 2), David Marrington (Region 3), And Paul C. Saraullo (Region 2) Paul Is the newest Member of the School Board beating Incumbent Bob Feather (Region 2). For a Region 2 seat on  November 5, 2019 (Election Day) and then was sworn onto the School Board on December 2, 2019 <ref>https://www.neshaminy.org/domain/1967</ref> The Board normally meets at the District Administration office in Maple Point Middle School twice a month. All meetings are broadcast on the NSDTV channel on Verizon and Comcast cable TV systems in the Lower Bucks County area or can viewed on the [https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCWSzcKzLZt0N9_artuBEYpA/videos Neshaminy School Board Channel on \nYouTube]\n\n\n\n==Intermediate Unit==\nNeshaminy School District is served by [https://www.bucksiu.org/ Bucks County Intermediate Unit #22.]\n\n[[File:NHS-1.jpg|thumb|Aerial view of Neshaminy High School]]\n\n==High school==\n===[[Neshaminy High School]]===\n\nNeshaminy High School is located at 2001 Old Lincoln Highway in Langhorne, PA. Enrollment as of January, 2020 is 2,573 students in grades 9-12. 327 Neshaminy students attend the Bucks County Technical High School. Neshaminy has a graduation rate of 95% and offers a rich variety of courses and co-curricular activities including 20 Advanced Placement courses<ref>https://www.usnews.com/education/best-high-schools/pennsylvania/districts/neshaminy-sd/neshaminy-high-school-17121/test-scores</ref>\n*[https://futurereadypa.org/Performance/123238108010045189089083010012180228205159115037/001232060191235024099229004013137247093037069080 Future Ready PA Index - Neshaminy High School] c\n\n==Middle schools==\n\n===Maple Point Middle School===\nLocated at 2250 Langhorne-Yardley Road, Langhorne. Enrollement as of January, 2020 is 1345 students in grades 5-8.\n*[https://futurereadypa.org/Performance/028228244236222235072090060245016072198063058188/151193013047060120155203102247122228153161155088 Future Ready PA Index - Maple Point Middle School]\n\n===Poquessing Middle School===\nLocated at 300 Heights Lane, Feasterville Trevose. Enrollment as January, 2020 is 931 students in grades 5-8.\n*[https://futurereadypa.org/Performance/089118177148132010036037029046024109092058107246/163037174175021028191115250006186134249130212215 Future Ready PA Index - Poquessing Middle School]\n\n===Carl Sandburg Middle School===\nLocated at 30 Harmony Road, Levittown. Enrollment as of January, 2020 is 755 students in grades 5-8.\n*[https://futurereadypa.org/Performance/251094080059105233137066092208074134166054234040/038139125129234005186169160252087050222143243012 Future Ready PA Index - Carl Sandburg Middle School]\n\n==Elementary schools==\n===Pearl S. Buck Elementary School===\nLocated at 143 Top Road, Levittown. Enrollment as of January, 2020 is 587 students in grades K-4. \n*[https://futurereadypa.org/Performance/223157169143250115000180180069023045096103149197/140147168146115058140197069003123203154180142014 Future Ready PA Index - Pearl S. Buck Elementary School]\n\n===Joseph E Ferderbar Elementary School===\nLocated at 300 Heights Lane, Feasterville. Enrollment as of January, 2020 is 473 students in grades K-4.\n*[https://futurereadypa.org/Performance/250057129020160133134009124218237132080121090200/023181213017026130127006125104035143143036117061239059038048191084007184056093014176071032031043 Future Ready PA Index - Joseph Ferderbar Elementary School]\n\n===Herbert Hoover Elementary School===\nLocated at 500 Trenton Road, Langhorne. Enrollment as of January, 2020 is 672 students in grades K-4.\n*[https://futurereadypa.org/Performance/132029143071137021091168188065001224163062100227/231234145094018140201190065209170156151237055191 Future Ready PA Index - Herbert Hoover Elementary School]\n\n===Walter Miller Elementary School=== \nLocated at 10 Cobalt Ridge Drive in Levittown, PA. Enrollment as of January, 2020 is 506 students in grades K-4.\n*[https://futurereadypa.org/Performance/018112152024132181089103157233184119157143252188/116088217111201144099251091195017161209231192068 Future Ready PA Index - Walter Miller Elementary School]\n\n===Albert Schweitzer Elementary School===\nLocated at 30 Harmony Lane in Levittown, PA. Enrollment as of January, 2020 is 432 students in grades K-4.\n*[https://futurereadypa.org/Performance/061056037221133008241050044000007061167050211005/020052196202219029081226234081073199222106051122091108205182052189089177162052212065030069216008 Future Ready PA Index - Albert Schweitzer Elementary School]\n\n===Tawanka Elementary School=== \nLocated at 2055 Brownsville Road in Feasterville, PA. The current building was completed in August, 2016 and opened for the 2016\u20132017 school year. It was built in the same site as the previous Tawanka Elementary School building, which opened in 1964 and was demolished to make way for the new facility. Enrollment as of January, 2020 is 763 students in grades K-4.\n*[https://futurereadypa.org/Performance/126108161194059186133218245145047247219093020229/025209004210100222090107233227095155008174133169 Future Ready PA Index - Tawanka Elementary School].\n\n==Special education==\n\nNeshaminy School District provides the following services:<ref>https://www.neshaminy.org/domain/2643</ref>\n\n'''Learning support''' \u2013 for children whose greatest need of support is in the areas of reading, writing, math, or speaking or listening related to academics.\n\n'''Emotional support''' \u2013 for children whose greatest need is for social, emotional, and behavioral help\nLife skills support \u2013 for children whose greatest need is to learn academic, functional, or vocational skills that will allow them to live and work independently.\n\n'''Blind and visually impaired support''' \u2013 for children who require services related to visual impairments or blindness. The IEP for these students must address the extent to which Braille will be taught and used.\n\n'''Deaf and hard of hearing support''' \u2013 for children who require services related to deafness or hearing impairment. The IEP for these students must include a communication plan to address language and communication needs\nSpeech and language support \u2013 for children who have speech and language impairments and require services to develop communication skills.\n\n'''Physical support''' \u2013 for children who have a physical disability and require services in functional motor skill development.\n\n'''Autistic support''' \u2013 for children with autism who require services in the areas of communication, social skills, or behavior.\n\n'''Multiple disabilities support''' \u2013 for children with more than one disability, the combination of which results in severe impairment, and who require services in academic, functional, or vocational skills necessary for independent living.\n\n==Gifted education==\n\nNeshaminy School District recognizes the unique abilities of intellectually gifted students and strives to meet their individual needs. Based on multiple criteria, students with outstanding intellectual ability and creativity and the need for a specialized educational experience are identified to participate in the AE (Academic Enrichment) program. AE classes provide opportunities to promote the growth of skills and knowledge necessary for gifted students to achieve their potential and to fulfill their future roles in our ever-changing global society.<ref>https://www.neshaminy.org/domain/1916</ref>\n\nIn 2015 a comprehensive review of the Academic enrichment was started and a Task Force report presented in June, 2016.<ref>https://www.neshaminy.org/cms/lib/PA01000466/Centricity/Domain/1916/AE-report-040116.pdf</ref> Based on the recommendations from this report changes were made to the program.<ref>https://www.neshaminy.org/cms/lib/PA01000466/Centricity/Domain/1916/ae-recommendations-121515a.pdf</ref>\n\n== Education Foundation ==\nThe non-profit 501(c)(3) [https://www.neshaminy.org/nef Neshaminy Education Foundation] was established as part of the District's Strategic Plan in 1993. It supports classroom grants and several scholarships for graduating seniors through a variety of fundraising activities throughout the year. The Foundation is managed by a group of volunteer Board Members who meet monthly during the school year.\n\n==Budget==\n\nIn June, 2019 the Neshaminy Board of School Directors adopted a Final Operating Budget of all funds in the amount of $185,853,953 for the 2019-2020 school year.\n\nOf this amount $119,939,505 was for instruction,$50,807,313 for support services and $1,963,207 for non-instructional services. \n\nAn tax increase of 2.3% (the PA Act 1 index maximum) was approved. This is the third such tax increase since 2010.<ref>https://www.neshaminy.org/site/handlers/filedownload.ashx?moduleinstanceid=43524&dataid=74979&FileName=2019-20%20Final%20PDE%202028%20for%20website.pdf</ref>\n\n==Contracts==\n'''Neshaminy Federation of Teachers''': The current teacher contract runs from July, 2019 to June, 2024.<ref>https://www.neshaminy.org/Page/37053</ref>\n\n'''Neshaminy Educational Support Professional Association''': The current support contract runs from July, 2018 - June, 2022.<ref>http://go.boarddocs.com/pa/nesh/Board.nsf/goto?open&id=BJ6QGH693F28</ref>\n\n==Real estate taxes==\nIn June, 2019 the School Board approved the third tax hike since the 2009\u20132010 school year, a 2.3% increase. This is the maximum increase allowed under the Pennsylvania Act 1 index. The district was granted an exemption that would have allowed a higher increase but the board chose not to use that option.<ref>http://levittownnow.com/2018/06/11/tax-increase-proposed-in-2018-2019-neshaminy-school-district-budget/</ref>\nThe district offers a Senior Citizen Tax Assistance Program each year. Eligible low-income seniors can apply for a rebate of up to $650.<ref>https://www.neshaminy.org/Page/758</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.neshaminy.org Neshaminy's official website]\n*[http://neshaminy.pa.aft.org/ Neshaminy Federation of Teachers]\n*[https://neshaminyesp.psealocals.org/ Neshaminy Educational Support Professional Association]\n*[https://www3.bucksiu.org/ Bucks County Intermediate Unit]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCWSzcKzLZt0N9_artuBEYpA/videos Board Meeting YouTube Channel]\n\n{{Bucks County, Pennsylvania School Districts}}\n\n[[Category:School districts in Bucks County, Pennsylvania]]\n", "name_user": "Bellowhead678", "label": "safe", "comment": "Enrollement->Enrollment -Fix a typo in one click", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neshaminy_School_District"}
{"title_page": "Jediism", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Path of the jedi|the episode of Star Wars Rebels|Path of the Jedi|the Disneyland attraction|Star Wars: Path of the Jedi}}\n{{for|the census campaign|Jedi census phenomenon}}\n{{pp-pc1}}\n{{short description|Philosophy mainly based on the Jedi characters in Star Wars media}}\n'''Jediism''' (or '''Jedism'''<ref name=LamontheWP>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2014/11/18/the-pentagons-pugnacious-critic-on-religion-gets-his-day-in-congress |title=The Pentagon\u2019s Pugnacious Critic on Religion Gets his Day in Congress |last=Lamonthe |first=Dan |publisher=Washington Post |date=18 November 2014 |website=Washington Post|access-date=20 November 2015}}</ref>) is a philosophy<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-38368526|title=Jedi is not a religion, Charity Commission rules|date=2016-12-19|newspaper=BBC News|access-date=2017-02-14|language=en-GB}}</ref> mainly based on the depiction of the [[Jedi]] characters in ''[[Star Wars]]'' media.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=exQ4Zmtjc_sC&pg=PA59|title=Popular spiritualities: the politics of contemporary enchantment|first=Lynne|last=Hume|first2=Kathleen|last2= McPhillips|page=59|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|year=2006| isbn=978-0-7546-3999-2}}</ref> Jediism attracted public attention in 2001 when a number of people [[Jedi census phenomenon|recorded their religion as \"Jedi\" on national censuses]].\n\nJediism is inspired by certain elements of ''Star Wars'', namely the fictional religion of the Jedi. Early websites dedicated to bringing up a belief system from the ''Star Wars'' films were \"The Jedi Religion and regulations\" and \"Jediism\". These websites cited the Jedi code, consisting of 21 maxims, as the starting point for a \"real Jedi\" belief system.<ref name=findingforce>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PB57P_dOF7EC&source=gbs_navlinks_s | title=Finding the Force in the Star Wars Franchise: Fans, Merchandise, and Critics | publisher=Peter Lang | author=Matthew Wilhelm Kapell|author2= John Shelton Lawrence | year=2006 | isbn=0-8204-6333-7}}</ref> The real-world Jediism movement has no founder or central structure.<ref name=\"D.Grant2008\">{{cite book|author1=Nancy K. Grant Ph. D.|author2=Ph. D. Diana J.|author3= Mansell R. N.|title=A Guidebook to Religious and Spiritual Practices for People Who Work With People|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eg5qZixgqbMC&pg=PA249|accessdate=16 July 2012|date=30 October 2008|publisher=iUniverse|isbn=978-0-595-50527-2|pages=249\u2013251}}</ref>\n\n== Beliefs ==\nThe Beliefs of The Jedi vary from Jedi to Jedi, however, the main belief is in the Force: an all binding energy that resides in all living things all over the universe, this means that we are all connected with the Force. The Force has the same rule of the energy in science: it cannot be created or destroyed. The Jedi are meant to be peacekeepers and are charitable, in real life a Jedi cannot use the Force like in the Star Wars movies, however they meditate and try to find inner peace. Jedi are supposed to reject the dark side and evil intentions that may cause harm to others. Some use the Jedi Code extracted from the Star Wars universe which consists of 5 core principles:\n\n\"There is no emotion, there is peace.\" - this principles guides all meditations and interactions with all others. It reaffirms the Jedi to act without recklessness.\n\n\"There is no ignorance, there is knowledge.\" - The Jedi who do not understand this basic precept are quick to fear and fear is the path to the dark side. \n\n\"There is no passion, there is serenity.\" - A subtle extrapolation of the first precept, this reminder to act dispassionately in every deliberation extends to personal obsessions. However, passion is not compassion and neither is love. To some Jedi, this principle can be taken to the extreme to not love people which is a natural feeling but can lead to attachment which can lead to fear and in turn the dark side.\n\n\"There is no chaos, there is harmony.\" - The Jedi are primarily peacekeepers and this principle tells them to. Chaos is the opposite of peace so the Jedi need to avoid chaos and bring harmony.\n\n\"There is no death, there is the Force.\" - All things die eventually but the force lives on. As beings exist as shades of the Force, the end of our existence in this form should not be overly mourned. The Jedi believe we are part of an energy larger than ourselves, and we play roles in a cosmic fabric that outstrip our incarnate understanding. What happens after death in the Jedi Order and everywhere else is up to debate there are two main theories in the Jedi Order: maintaining consciousness after death or becoming the Force, both of which are very popular.\n\nThe Belief System of the Jedi take from Sikhism and Buddhism and also have their own beliefs. The belief of energy shares with Buddhism and some of the customs of the Jedi share with Sikhism.\n\nThe Jedi are often mistaken to believe in the Star Wars universe and the characters within but that isn't true they take beliefs of the Jedi from the Star Wars movies and are often misunderstood.\n\n== Census phenomenon ==\n{{Main|Jedi census phenomenon}}\n\nJediism received press coverage following a worldwide email campaign in 2001 urging people to write \"Jedi\" as their answer to the religion classification question in their country's census, resulting in the [[Jedi census phenomenon]]. The majority of such respondents are assumed to have claimed the faith as a joke.<ref name=\"census\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/religion/9737886/Jedi-religion-most-popular-alternative-faith.html|title='Jedi' religion most popular alternative faith|publisher=Telegraph Media Group|work=The Daily Telegraph|first=Henry|last=Taylor|date=2012-12-11|accessdate=2012-12-14|location=London}}</ref><ref name=\"Cusack2010\">{{cite book|author=Carole M. Cusack|title=Invented Religions: Faith, Fiction, Imagination|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EoduVhGsfp0C&pg=PA125|accessdate=4 January 2013|date=15 September 2010|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|isbn=978-0-7546-6780-3|page=125}}</ref><ref name=\"nzherald\">{{Cite news|url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=2352142|title = Jedi Order lures 53,000 disciples|date = August 31, 2002|accessdate = July 30, 2013|website = [[The New Zealand Herald]]|publisher = [[APN News & Media]]|last = Perrott|first = Alan}}</ref>\n\n== Legal recognition ==\n\n=== United States ===\nIn 2005, the Temple of the Jedi Order was registered in [[Texas]]. It was granted [[Internal Revenue Service|IRS]] tax exemption in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.templeofthejediorder.org/images/TOTJO-IRS-Exemption-Letter.pdf|title=IRS Determination Letter}}</ref>\n\n=== United Kingdom ===\nDuring the drafting of the UK [[Racial and Religious Hatred Act 2006|Racial and Religious Hatred Act]], an amendment was proposed that excluded Jedi Knights from any protection, along with [[Satanist]]s and believers in [[animal sacrifice]]. The amendment was subsequently withdrawn, the proposer explaining that it was \"a bit of a joke\" to illustrate a point that defining religious belief in legislation is difficult.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200506/cmstand/e/st050629/pm/50629s01.htm|accessdate=2010-02-22|title=Racial and Religious Hatred Bill|date=2005-06-29}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wells|first1=Jonathan|title=Inside the Church of Jediism: what it's like to follow The Force|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/men/thinking-man/inside-the-church-of-jediism-what-its-like-to-follow-the-force/|accessdate=7 January 2017|publisher=Telegraph|date=2015-12-15}}</ref> 23-year-old Daniel Jones founded The Church of Jediism with his brother Barney, believing that the 2001 UK census recognised Jediism as a religion, and that there were \"more Jedi than Scientologists in Britain\".<ref name=\"Cusack2010\" /> In 2009, Jones was removed from a [[Tesco]] supermarket in [[Bangor, Gwynedd|Bangor]], North Wales, for refusing to remove his hood on a religious basis. The owner justified Jones's ejection by saying, \"He hasn't been banned. Jedis are very welcome to shop in our stores although we would ask them to remove their hoods. [[Obi-Wan Kenobi]], [[Yoda]] and [[Luke Skywalker]] all appeared hoodless without ever going over to the [[Dark side (Star Wars)|Dark Side]] and we are only aware of [[Palpatine|the Emperor]] as one who never removed his hood.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/sep/18/jedi-religion-tesco-hood-jones|publisher=The Guardian|title=Jedi religion founder accuses Tesco of discrimination over rules on hoods|accessdate=2011-02-22|first=Helen|last=Carter|location=London|date=18 September 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, a man who described himself as a \"Star Wars follower\" and \"Jedi Knight\" was thrown out of a [[Jobcentre Plus|Jobcentre]] in [[Southend]], [[Essex]], for refusing to remove his hood, and later received an apology. The man said that \"The main reason is I want to wear my hood up, and I have got a religion which allows me to do that.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1258365/Jedi-believer-wins-apology-Jobcentre-kicked-wearing-hood.html|publisher=The Daily Mail|title=Political correctness strikes back: Jedi believer wins apology after being kicked out of Jobcentre for wearing a hood|first=Andrew|last=Levy|date=2010-03-17|accessdate=2011-02-22|location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, the [[Free Church of Scotland (post-1900)|Free Church of Scotland]] expressed concern that a proposed [[Marriage and Civil Partnership (Scotland) Bill|Marriage and Civil Partnership bill]] would \"lead to Star Wars Jedi marrying couples\". Patrick Day-Childs of The Church of Jediism, and Rev Michael Kitchen of Temple of the Jedi Order, both defended the right of Jedi to perform marriage ceremonies.<ref>McKenzie, Steven [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-highlands-islands-21844467 \"Star chores: Do Jedi want to marry people?\"], ''[[BBC News]]'', London, 20 March 2013. Retrieved on 14 June 2014.</ref><ref>Hudson, Tony [http://www.politics.co.uk/news/2013/03/25/marry-you-i-will-jedi-strike-back-against-church-on-weddings \"Marry you, I will: Jedi strike back over weddings criticism\"], ''Politics UK'', 25 March 2013. Retrieved on 14 June 2014.</ref>\n\nIn December 2016, the [[Charity Commission for England and Wales]] rejected an application to grant [[Charitable organization#England and Wales|charitable organization]] status to The Temple of the Jedi Order, ruling that the group did not \"promote moral or ethical improvement\" for charity law purposes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-38368526|title=Jediism not a religion, Charity Commission rules|work=[[BBC News]]|date=19 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Turkey ===\n\nIn April 2015, the students of [[Dokuz Eyl\u00fcl University]] in [[Turkey]] started a petition on [[Change.org]] demanding a Jedi temple be built on the campus. The petition was in response to a previous petition which had demanded a mosque on the campus of [[Istanbul Technical University]] (\u0130T\u00dc). The petition demanding the mosque reached 180,000 signatures, falling short of its 200,000 target, and invoked a response from [[Mehmet Karaca]], the [[rector (academia)|rector]] of Istanbul Technical University (\u0130T\u00dc), promising \"a landmark mosque\". Soon after, students from other universities started petitions demanding Jedi and Buddhist temples on their campuses.<ref name=CampusJedi>{{cite news|title=Thousands of Turkish students sign petition to build Jedi Temple on university campus|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/thousands-of-turkish-students-sign-petition-to-build-jedi-temple-on-university-campus-10161225.html|accessdate=8 April 2015|work=[[The Independent]]|date=8 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=JediTurkey>{{cite news|title=Turkish University students demand Jedi, Buddhist temples amid mosque frenzy|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkish-university-students-demand-jedi-buddhist-temples-amid-mosque-frenzy.aspx?PageID=238&NID=80634&NewsCatID=341|accessdate=8 April 2015|work=Hurriyet Daily News|date=6 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of religious ideas in science fiction]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q258945|s=no|wikt=Jediism|c=category:Jediism|n=no|b=no|voy=no|v=no|q=no|m=no|mw=no|species=no}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.templeofthejediorder.org/doctrine-of-the-order |title=Doctrine of the Temple of the Jedi Order |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180317084203/https://www.templeofthejediorder.org/doctrine-of-the-order |archivedate=17 March 2018}}\n*{{Curlie|Society/Religion_and_Spirituality/Fictional/Jediism/}}\n*[http://www.patheos.com/blogs/altmuslim/2005/06/star_wars_an_islamic_perspective/ Inspiration: Star Wars: An Islamic perspective]\n* {{cite web |title=To Be A Jedi |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/w3csy2py |website=Heart And Soul |publisher=[[BBC World Service]] |accessdate=21 December 2018}}\n\n{{Religion topics}}\n{{Star Wars}}\n\n[[Category:Jedi]]\n[[Category:New religious movements]]\n[[Category:Subcultures of religious movements]]\n[[Category:2001 in religion]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Path of the jedi|the episode of Star Wars Rebels|Path of the Jedi|the Disneyland attraction|Star Wars: Path of the Jedi}}\n{{for|the census campaign|Jedi census phenomenon}}\n{{pp-pc1}}\n{{short description|Philosophy mainly based on the Jedi characters in Star Wars media}}\n'''Jediism''' (or '''Jedism'''<ref name=LamontheWP>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2014/11/18/the-pentagons-pugnacious-critic-on-religion-gets-his-day-in-congress |title=The Pentagon\u2019s Pugnacious Critic on Religion Gets his Day in Congress |last=Lamonthe |first=Dan |publisher=Washington Post |date=18 November 2014 |website=Washington Post|access-date=20 November 2015}}</ref>) is a philosophy<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-38368526|title=Jedi is not a religion, Charity Commission rules|date=2016-12-19|newspaper=BBC News|access-date=2017-02-14|language=en-GB}}</ref> mainly based on the depiction of the [[Jedi]] characters in ''[[Star Wars]]'' media.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=exQ4Zmtjc_sC&pg=PA59|title=Popular spiritualities: the politics of contemporary enchantment|first=Lynne|last=Hume|first2=Kathleen|last2= McPhillips|page=59|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|year=2006| isbn=978-0-7546-3999-2}}</ref> Jediism attracted public attention in 2001 when a number of people [[Jedi census phenomenon|recorded their religion as \"Jedi\" on national censuses]].\n\nJediism is inspired by certain elements of ''Star Wars'', namely the fictional religion of the Jedi. Early websites dedicated to bringing up a belief system from the ''Star Wars'' films were \"The Jedi Religion and regulations\" and \"Jediism\". These websites cited the Jedi code, consisting of 21 maxims, as the starting point for a \"real Jedi\" belief system.<ref name=findingforce>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PB57P_dOF7EC&source=gbs_navlinks_s | title=Finding the Force in the Star Wars Franchise: Fans, Merchandise, and Critics | publisher=Peter Lang | author=Matthew Wilhelm Kapell|author2= John Shelton Lawrence | year=2006 | isbn=0-8204-6333-7}}</ref> The real-world Jediism movement has no founder or central structure.<ref name=\"D.Grant2008\">{{cite book|author1=Nancy K. Grant Ph. D.|author2=Ph. D. Diana J.|author3= Mansell R. N.|title=A Guidebook to Religious and Spiritual Practices for People Who Work With People|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eg5qZixgqbMC&pg=PA249|accessdate=16 July 2012|date=30 October 2008|publisher=iUniverse|isbn=978-0-595-50527-2|pages=249\u2013251}}</ref>\n\n== Beliefs ==\nAlthough followers of Jediism acknowledge the influence of ''Star Wars'' on their religion, by following the moral and spiritual codes demonstrated by the fictional Jedi,<ref>{{cite book | title=Exploring religion and the sacred in a media age | last=Deacy|first=Christopher|first2= Elisabeth |last2=Arweck | page=15|url=https://books.google.com/?id=HRmYapWETqcC&pg=PA15&dq=jediism#v=onepage&q=jediism&f=false|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|year=2009 | isbn=978-0-7546-6527-4}}</ref> they also insist their path is different from that of the fictional characters and that Jediism does not focus on the myth and fiction found in ''Star Wars''.<ref name=\"KapellLawrence2006\">{{cite book|author1=Matthew Kapell|author2=John Shelton Lawrence|title=Finding the Force of the Star Wars Franchise: Fans, Merchandise, & Critics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PB57P_dOF7EC&pg=PA106|accessdate=16 July 2012|date=1 August 2006|publisher=Peter Lang|isbn=978-0-8204-6333-9|pages=105\u2013112}}</ref>\nWhile there is some variation in teaching, the Jedi of the Temple of the Jedi Order follows the \"16 teachings\" based on the presentation of the fictional Jedi, such as \"Jedi are mindful of the negative emotions which lead to the Dark Side\" and \"Jedi are guardians of peace and justice\".<ref name=about.com>{{cite web|url=http://altreligion.about.com/od/beliefsandcreeds/a/jedi_teachings.htm|accessdate=6 September 2013|title=Basic teachings of the Jedi|first=Catherine|last=Beyer|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|work=[[About.com]]}}</ref> Adherents also follow \"21 maxims\".<ref name=findingforce /><ref name=doctrine>{{cite web|url=http://www.templeofthejediorder.org/doctrine-of-the-order|accessdate=6 September 2013|title=Doctrine of the Temple of the Jedi Order|publisher=Temple of the Jedi Order}}</ref>\n\n== Census phenomenon ==\n{{Main|Jedi census phenomenon}}\n\nJediism received press coverage following a worldwide email campaign in 2001 urging people to write \"Jedi\" as their answer to the religion classification question in their country's census, resulting in the [[Jedi census phenomenon]]. The majority of such respondents are assumed to have claimed the faith as a joke.<ref name=\"census\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/religion/9737886/Jedi-religion-most-popular-alternative-faith.html|title='Jedi' religion most popular alternative faith|publisher=Telegraph Media Group|work=The Daily Telegraph|first=Henry|last=Taylor|date=2012-12-11|accessdate=2012-12-14|location=London}}</ref><ref name=\"Cusack2010\">{{cite book|author=Carole M. Cusack|title=Invented Religions: Faith, Fiction, Imagination|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EoduVhGsfp0C&pg=PA125|accessdate=4 January 2013|date=15 September 2010|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|isbn=978-0-7546-6780-3|page=125}}</ref><ref name=\"nzherald\">{{Cite news|url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=2352142|title = Jedi Order lures 53,000 disciples|date = August 31, 2002|accessdate = July 30, 2013|website = [[The New Zealand Herald]]|publisher = [[APN News & Media]]|last = Perrott|first = Alan}}</ref>\n\n== Legal recognition ==\n\n=== United States ===\nIn 2005, the Temple of the Jedi Order was registered in [[Texas]]. It was granted [[Internal Revenue Service|IRS]] tax exemption in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.templeofthejediorder.org/images/TOTJO-IRS-Exemption-Letter.pdf|title=IRS Determination Letter}}</ref>\n\n=== United Kingdom ===\nDuring the drafting of the UK [[Racial and Religious Hatred Act 2006|Racial and Religious Hatred Act]], an amendment was proposed that excluded Jedi Knights from any protection, along with [[Satanist]]s and believers in [[animal sacrifice]]. The amendment was subsequently withdrawn, the proposer explaining that it was \"a bit of a joke\" to illustrate a point that defining religious belief in legislation is difficult.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200506/cmstand/e/st050629/pm/50629s01.htm|accessdate=2010-02-22|title=Racial and Religious Hatred Bill|date=2005-06-29}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wells|first1=Jonathan|title=Inside the Church of Jediism: what it's like to follow The Force|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/men/thinking-man/inside-the-church-of-jediism-what-its-like-to-follow-the-force/|accessdate=7 January 2017|publisher=Telegraph|date=2015-12-15}}</ref> 23-year-old Daniel Jones founded The Church of Jediism with his brother Barney, believing that the 2001 UK census recognised Jediism as a religion, and that there were \"more Jedi than Scientologists in Britain\".<ref name=\"Cusack2010\" /> In 2009, Jones was removed from a [[Tesco]] supermarket in [[Bangor, Gwynedd|Bangor]], North Wales, for refusing to remove his hood on a religious basis. The owner justified Jones's ejection by saying, \"He hasn't been banned. Jedis are very welcome to shop in our stores although we would ask them to remove their hoods. [[Obi-Wan Kenobi]], [[Yoda]] and [[Luke Skywalker]] all appeared hoodless without ever going over to the [[Dark side (Star Wars)|Dark Side]] and we are only aware of [[Palpatine|the Emperor]] as one who never removed his hood.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/sep/18/jedi-religion-tesco-hood-jones|publisher=The Guardian|title=Jedi religion founder accuses Tesco of discrimination over rules on hoods|accessdate=2011-02-22|first=Helen|last=Carter|location=London|date=18 September 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, a man who described himself as a \"Star Wars follower\" and \"Jedi Knight\" was thrown out of a [[Jobcentre Plus|Jobcentre]] in [[Southend]], [[Essex]], for refusing to remove his hood, and later received an apology. The man said that \"The main reason is I want to wear my hood up, and I have got a religion which allows me to do that.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1258365/Jedi-believer-wins-apology-Jobcentre-kicked-wearing-hood.html|publisher=The Daily Mail|title=Political correctness strikes back: Jedi believer wins apology after being kicked out of Jobcentre for wearing a hood|first=Andrew|last=Levy|date=2010-03-17|accessdate=2011-02-22|location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, the [[Free Church of Scotland (post-1900)|Free Church of Scotland]] expressed concern that a proposed [[Marriage and Civil Partnership (Scotland) Bill|Marriage and Civil Partnership bill]] would \"lead to Star Wars Jedi marrying couples\". Patrick Day-Childs of The Church of Jediism, and Rev Michael Kitchen of Temple of the Jedi Order, both defended the right of Jedi to perform marriage ceremonies.<ref>McKenzie, Steven [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-highlands-islands-21844467 \"Star chores: Do Jedi want to marry people?\"], ''[[BBC News]]'', London, 20 March 2013. Retrieved on 14 June 2014.</ref><ref>Hudson, Tony [http://www.politics.co.uk/news/2013/03/25/marry-you-i-will-jedi-strike-back-against-church-on-weddings \"Marry you, I will: Jedi strike back over weddings criticism\"], ''Politics UK'', 25 March 2013. Retrieved on 14 June 2014.</ref>\n\nIn December 2016, the [[Charity Commission for England and Wales]] rejected an application to grant [[Charitable organization#England and Wales|charitable organization]] status to The Temple of the Jedi Order, ruling that the group did not \"promote moral or ethical improvement\" for charity law purposes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-38368526|title=Jediism not a religion, Charity Commission rules|work=[[BBC News]]|date=19 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Turkey ===\n\nIn April 2015, the students of [[Dokuz Eyl\u00fcl University]] in [[Turkey]] started a petition on [[Change.org]] demanding a Jedi temple be built on the campus. The petition was in response to a previous petition which had demanded a mosque on the campus of [[Istanbul Technical University]] (\u0130T\u00dc). The petition demanding the mosque reached 180,000 signatures, falling short of its 200,000 target, and invoked a response from [[Mehmet Karaca]], the [[rector (academia)|rector]] of Istanbul Technical University (\u0130T\u00dc), promising \"a landmark mosque\". Soon after, students from other universities started petitions demanding Jedi and Buddhist temples on their campuses.<ref name=CampusJedi>{{cite news|title=Thousands of Turkish students sign petition to build Jedi Temple on university campus|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/thousands-of-turkish-students-sign-petition-to-build-jedi-temple-on-university-campus-10161225.html|accessdate=8 April 2015|work=[[The Independent]]|date=8 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=JediTurkey>{{cite news|title=Turkish University students demand Jedi, Buddhist temples amid mosque frenzy|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkish-university-students-demand-jedi-buddhist-temples-amid-mosque-frenzy.aspx?PageID=238&NID=80634&NewsCatID=341|accessdate=8 April 2015|work=Hurriyet Daily News|date=6 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of religious ideas in science fiction]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q258945|s=no|wikt=Jediism|c=category:Jediism|n=no|b=no|voy=no|v=no|q=no|m=no|mw=no|species=no}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.templeofthejediorder.org/doctrine-of-the-order |title=Doctrine of the Temple of the Jedi Order |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180317084203/https://www.templeofthejediorder.org/doctrine-of-the-order |archivedate=17 March 2018}}\n*{{Curlie|Society/Religion_and_Spirituality/Fictional/Jediism/}}\n*[http://www.patheos.com/blogs/altmuslim/2005/06/star_wars_an_islamic_perspective/ Inspiration: Star Wars: An Islamic perspective]\n* {{cite web |title=To Be A Jedi |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/w3csy2py |website=Heart And Soul |publisher=[[BBC World Service]] |accessdate=21 December 2018}}\n\n{{Religion topics}}\n{{Star Wars}}\n\n[[Category:Jedi]]\n[[Category:New religious movements]]\n[[Category:Subcultures of religious movements]]\n[[Category:2001 in religion]]\n", "name_user": "CaptainFerrara", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eBeliefs:Added content and deleted false content that mislead readers. I added facts)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jediism"}
{"title_page": "Malory Towers (TV series)", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Malory Towers\n| caption                  = \n| image                    = \n| genre                    = \n| based_on                 = {{Based on|''[[Malory Towers]]''|[[Enid Blyton]]}}\n| creator                  = \n| starring                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Ella Bright\n}}\n| writer                   = {{Plainlist|\n* Sasha Hails\n* Rachel Flowerday\n}}\n| director                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Rebecca Rycroft\n* [[Bruce McDonald (director)|Bruce McDonald]]\n}}\n| opentheme                =\n| country                  = \n| language                 = English\n| num_series               = 1\n| num_episodes             = 13\n| list_episodes            =\n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Josh Scherba\n* Anne Loi\n* Michael Goldsmith\n* Jo Sargent\n}}\n| producer                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Grainne McNamara\n* Angela Boudreault\n}}\n| location                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[England]]\n* [[Canada]]\n}}\n| runtime                  =\n| company                  = {{Plainlist|\n* [[DHX Media]]\n* King Bert Productions\n}}\n| network                  = {{Plainlist|\n* [[CBBC]]\n* [[Family Channel (Canadian TV network)|Family Channel]]\n}}\n| picture_format           =\n| audio_format             =\n| first_aired              = \n| last_aired               =\n| related                  =\n| website                  = \n| num_series               =\n| editor                   =\n}}\n\n'''''Malory Towers''''' is a British-Canadian television series based on the [[Malory Towers|eponymous book series]] by [[Enid Blyton]]. The 12 episodes were available early on [[BBC iPlayer]] on 23 March 2020, the first of which is set to air on [[CBBC]] on 6 April 2020 in the United Kingdom.\n\n==Premise==\nSet in post-World War II Britain, the show follows the adventures of 12-year-old Darrell Rivers as she leaves home to attend an all-girls' boarding school and \"explores a nostalgic world of midnight feasts, lacrosse, pranks, a mystery ghost and lasting friendships.\"\n\n==Cast==\n* Ella Bright as Darrell Rivers\n* Danya Griver as Gwendoline Mary Lacey\n* Zoey Siewert as Alicia Johns\n* Sienna Arif-Knights as Sally Hope\n* Twinkle Jaiswal as Katherine\n* Imogen Lamb as Mary-Lou\n* Natasha Raphael as Irene\n* Saskia Kemkers as Emily\n* Beth Bradfield as Jean\n* Hannah Saxby as Pamela\n* Ashley McGuire as Matron\n* Genevieve Beaudet as Mam'zelle Rougier\n* Imali Perera as Miss Potts\n* Jennifer Wigmore as Miss Grayling\n* Christine Horne as Margaret\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Episode table |background=#000000 |overall= |title= |director= |writer= |airdate= |airdateR= |released=y |country=US |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 1\n |Title           = The First Day\n |DirectedBy     = Bruce McDonald\n |WrittenBy       = Rachel Flowerday & Sasha Hails\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|||df=y}}\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 2\n |Title           = The New Girls\n |DirectedBy    = Bruce McDonald\n |WrittenBy       = Julie Dixon\n |OriginalAirDate = 2020\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 3\n |Title           = The Trick\n |DirectedBy      = Bruce McDonald\n |WrittenBy       = Richie Conroy & Mark Hodkinson\n |OriginalAirDate = 2020\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 4\n |Title           = The Slap\n |DirectedBy      = Rebecca Rycroft\n |WrittenBy      = Rachel Flowerday & Sasha Hails\n |OriginalAirDate = 2020\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 5\n |Title           = The Match\n |DirectedBy      = Rebecca Rycroft\n |WrittenBy       = Rachel Flowerday & Sasha Hails\n |OriginalAirDate = 2020\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 6\n |Title           = The Midnight Feast\n |DirectedBy      = Rebecca Rycroft\n |WrittenBy       = Julia Kent\n |OriginalAirDate = 2020\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 7\n |Title           = The Open Day\n |DirectedBy      = Rebecca Rycroft\n |WrittenBy       = Kate Hewlett\n |OriginalAirDate = 2020\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 8\n |Title           = The Push\n |DirectedBy      = Rebecca Rycroft\n |WrittenBy       = Rachel Flowerday & Sasha Hails\n |OriginalAirDate = 2020\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 9\n |Title           = The Letter\n |DirectedBy      = Rebecca Rycroft\n |WrittenBy       = Rachel Flowerday & Sasha Hails\n |OriginalAirDate = 2020\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 10\n |Title           = The Dress\n |DirectedBy      = Bruce McDonald\n |WrittenBy       = Richie Conroy & Mark Hodkinson\n |OriginalAirDate = 2020\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 11\n |Title           = The Spider\n |DirectedBy      = Bruce McDonald\n |WrittenBy       = Richie Conroy & Mark Hodkinson\n |OriginalAirDate = 2020\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 12\n |Title           = The Ghost\n |DirectedBy      = Bruce McDonald\n |WrittenBy       = Kate Hewlett\n |OriginalAirDate = 2020\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 13\n |Title           = The Last Day\n |DirectedBy      = Bruce McDonald\n |WrittenBy       = Rachel Flowerday & Sasha Hails\n |OriginalAirDate = 2020\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 000\n}}\n}}\n\n==Production==\nIn July 2019, it was announced in a press release that [[CBBC]] and [[Family Channel (Canadian TV network)|Family Channel]] had commissioned a 13-part co-produced adaptation of [[Enid Blyton]]'s ''[[Malory Towers]]''. Sasha Hails and Rachel Flowerday would adapt the series for television with Rebecca Rycroft and [[Bruce McDonald (director)|Bruce McDonald]] directing. From [[DHX Media]], Josh Scherba, Anne Loi and Michael Goldsmith are executive producing; Angela Boudreault is producing. From King Bert Productions, Jo Sargent is executive producing and Grainne McNamara is producing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.licensingmagazine.com/2019/07/10/cbbc-and-family-channel-commission-malory-towers/?lang=en|title=CBBC and Family Channel commission Malory Towers|journal=Licensing Magazine|date=10 July 2019|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nPrincipal photography began in [[Toronto]], Canada in summer 2019 and later moved to in [[Cornwall]] and [[Devon]] in England, shooting at [[Hartland Abbey]] and in the town of [[Bodmin]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2020/mar/20/downton-for-kids-bbc-brings-forward-malory-towers-adaptation|title='Downton for kids': BBC brings forward Malory Towers adaptation|journal=The Guardian|first=Tara|last=Conlan|date=20 March 2020|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n[[CBBC]] released a teaser trailer on 20 March 2020 with the announcement that the series would premiere on 6 April 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/TV/2020/03/22/Malory-Towers-series-to-premiere-on-CBBC-April-6/2281584882702/|title='Malory Towers' series to premiere on CBBC April 6|journal=The Guardian|first=Karen|last=Butler|date=22 March 2020|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> The episodes were available to view early on [[BBC iPlayer]] as of 23 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodhousekeeping.com/uk/lifestyle/a31892161/bbc-malory-towers-adaption-iplayer/|title=BBC's new Malory Towers adaption arrives on iPlayer early|journal=Good Housekeeping|first=Elena|last=Chabo|date=23 March 2020|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref> The Canada release date is yet to be announced.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|11129816}}\n\n[[Category:2020 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2020s British children's television series]]\n[[Category:2020s Canadian children's television series]]\n[[Category:BBC children's television programmes]]\n[[Category:British television programmes based on children's books]]\n[[Category:Canadian television programs based on children's books]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Malory Towers\n| caption                  = \n| image                    = \n| genre                    = \n| based_on                 = {{Based on|''[[Malory Towers]]''|[[Enid Blyton]]}}\n| creator                  = \n| starring                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Ella Bright\n}}\n| writer                   = {{Plainlist|\n* Sasha Hails\n* Rachel Flowerday\n}}\n| director                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Rebecca Rycroft\n* [[Bruce McDonald (director)|Bruce McDonald]]\n}}\n| opentheme                =\n| country                  = \n| language                 = English\n| num_episodes             = 13\n| list_episodes            =\n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Josh Scherba\n* Anne Loi\n* Michael Goldsmith\n* Jo Sargent\n}}\n| producer                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Grainne McNamara\n* Angela Boudreault\n}}\n| location                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[England]]\n* [[Canada]]\n}}\n| runtime                  =\n| company                  = {{Plainlist|\n* [[DHX Media]]\n* King Bert Productions\n}}\n| network                  = {{Plainlist|\n* [[CBBC]]\n* [[Family Channel (Canadian TV network)|Family Channel]]\n}}\n| picture_format           =\n| audio_format             =\n| first_aired              = \n| last_aired               =\n| related                  =\n| website                  = \n| num_series               =\n| editor                   =\n}}\n\n'''''Malory Towers''''' is a British-Canadian television series based on the [[Malory Towers|eponymous book series]] by [[Enid Blyton]]. The 12 episodes were available early on [[BBC iPlayer]] on 23 March 2020, the first of which is set to air on [[CBBC]] on 6 April 2020 in the United Kingdom.\n\n==Premise==\nSet in post-World War II Britain, the show follows the adventures of 12-year-old Darrell Rivers as she leaves home to attend an all-girls' boarding school and \"explores a nostalgic world of midnight feasts, lacrosse, pranks, a mystery ghost and lasting friendships.\"\n\n==Cast==\n* Ella Bright as Darrell Rivers\n* Danya Griver as Gwendoline Mary Lacey\n* Zoey Siewert as Alicia Johns\n* Sienna Arif-Knights as Sally Hope\n* Twinkle Jaiswal as Katherine\n* Imogen Lamb as Mary-Lou\n* Natasha Raphael as Irene\n* Saskia Kemkers as Emily\n* Beth Bradfield as Jean\n* Hannah Saxby as Pamela\n* Ashley McGuire as Matron\n* Genevieve Beaudet as Mam'zelle Rougier\n* Imali Perera as Miss Potts\n* Jennifer Wigmore as Miss Grayling\n* Christine Horne as Margaret\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Episode table |background=#000000 |overall= |title= |director= |writer= |airdate= |airdateR= |released=y |country=US |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 1\n |Title           = The First Day\n |DirectedBy     = Bruce McDonald\n |WrittenBy       = Rachel Flowerday & Sasha Hails\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|||df=y}}\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 2\n |Title           = The New Girls\n |DirectedBy    = Bruce McDonald\n |WrittenBy       = Julie Dixon\n |OriginalAirDate = 2020\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 3\n |Title           = The Trick\n |DirectedBy      = Bruce McDonald\n |WrittenBy       = Richie Conroy & Mark Hodkinson\n |OriginalAirDate = 2020\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 4\n |Title           = The Slap\n |DirectedBy      = Rebecca Rycroft\n |WrittenBy      = Rachel Flowerda